{"topicId":"positive-definite-matrices-markov","mcqs":[{"id":"mcq-1","question":"Consider a symmetric matrix A ∈ ℝ^n×n. Which of the following statements is the CORRECT and COMPLETE definition of A being positive definite?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"A is positive definite if all its eigenvalues are positive."},{"key":"B","text":"A is positive definite if x^TAx > 0 for all non-zero vectors x ∈ ℝ^n."},{"key":"C","text":"A is positive definite if it has a Cholesky decomposition A = LL^T where L is lower triangular with positive diagonal entries."},{"key":"D","text":"A is positive definite if its leading principal minors are positive (Sylvester's criterion)."}],"correctAnswer":"B","explanation":"The definition x^TAx > 0 for ALL non-zero x is the fundamental definition; eigenvalues, Cholesky, and Sylvester's criterion are equivalent CHARACTERIZATIONS for symmetric matrices, not definitions.","difficulty":"easy"},{"id":"mcq-2","question":"For a positive definite matrix A, which of the following is ALWAYS true?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"A has a square root matrix B such that B^2 = A."},{"key":"B","text":"A can be written as B^TB for some invertible matrix B."},{"key":"C","text":"The diagonal entries of A are all positive."},{"key":"D","text":"All of the above are always true for any positive definite matrix."}],"correctAnswer":"D","explanation":"All three statements hold: the eigendecomposition gives A^(1/2); A = LL^T gives B = L^T; and x^TAx > 0 with x = e_i gives a_ii > 0.","difficulty":"easy"},{"id":"mcq-3","question":"In machine learning, the Gaussian radial basis function (RBF) kernel K(x, y) = exp(-||x - y||²/2σ²) is widely used in Support Vector Machines. Why must this kernel matrix be positive definite for ANY finite set of data points?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"It ensures the kernel matrix is invertible and can be used for classification."},{"key":"B","text":"It guarantees the kernel corresponds to a valid feature space mapping (Mercer's theorem) and the optimization problem remains convex."},{"key":"C","text":"It makes the kernel matrix symmetric, which is required for any kernel function."},{"key":"D","text":"It ensures the SVM decision boundary passes through the origin."}],"correctAnswer":"B","explanation":"Positive definiteness of the kernel is required by Mercer's theorem to guarantee a valid inner product in some feature space, which ensures the SVM optimization problem is convex with a global optimum.","difficulty":"medium"},{"id":"mcq-4","question":"In a Markov chain with transition matrix P, thePageRank algorithm models a random walk on the web graph. What role does the damping factor α (typically 0.85) play in the modified transition matrix?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"It ensures the transition matrix is stochastic (rows sum to 1)."},{"key":"B","text":"It makes the Markov chain irreducible and aperiodic, guaranteeing a unique stationary distribution (the PageRank vector)."},{"key":"C","text":"It reduces the computational complexity of computing the stationary distribution."},{"key":"D","text":"It converts a positive definite matrix into a stochastic matrix."}],"correctAnswer":"B","explanation":"The damping factor creates a irreducible, aperiodic chain (the Google matrix G = αP + (1-α)/n J), ensuring the Perron-Frobenius theorem applies and guarantees a unique stationary distribution as the PageRank.","difficulty":"medium"},{"id":"mcq-5","question":"Let A be a 3×3 symmetric positive definite matrix. Which of the following is NOT a valid method to verify positive definiteness of A?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"Check if all leading principal minors are positive."},{"key":"B","text":"Check if all eigenvalues are positive."},{"key":"C","text":"Check if the matrix can be factored as A = LL^T with positive diagonal entries."},{"key":"D","text":"Check if A⁻¹ exists (matrix is invertible)."}],"correctAnswer":"D","explanation":"While positive definite matrices are always invertible, the converse is not true: an invertible matrix need not be positive definite (e.g., a negative definite matrix is also invertible). Invertibility is necessary but not sufficient.","difficulty":"medium"},{"id":"mcq-6","question":"Consider the quadratic function f(x) = x^TAx + b^x + c in ℝ^n, where A is symmetric. Which condition on A ensures that f(x) has a unique global minimum?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"A is positive semidefinite and b is in the column space of A."},{"key":"B","text":"A is positive definite (all eigenvalues > 0)."},{"key":"C","text":"A is negative definite."},{"key":"D","text":"A is singular but b = 0."}],"definite","explanation":"Positive definiteness of A guarantees convexity (f is a convex function) and ensures the Hessian is positive definite, leading to a unique global minimum at x* = -½A⁻¹b.","difficulty":"medium"},{"id":"mcq-7","question":"Let P be the transition matrix of a Markov chain. Which property guarantees that the chain has a unique stationary distribution π regardless of the initial distribution?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"P is symmetric."},{"key":"B","text":"P is positive definite."},{"key":"C","text":"P is primitive (some power P^k has all positive entries), implying irreducibility and aperiodicity."},{"key":"D","text":"P has 1 as a simple eigenvalue and all other eigenvalues have absolute value < 1."}],"correctAnswer":"C","explanation":"By the Perron-Frobenius theorem, a primitive (or irreducible + aperiodic) stochastic matrix guarantees a unique stationary distribution; this is why the damping factor in PageRank ensures convergence.","difficulty":"hard"},{"id":"mcq-8","question":"Given the symmetric matrix A = [[2, -1, 0], [-1, 2, -1], [0, -1, 2]], which of the following statements is FALSE about A?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"A is positive definite because its eigenvalues are 2, 2-√2, and 2+√2, all positive."},{"key":"B","text":"A can be factored as LL^T where L = [[√2, 0, 0], [-1/√2, √(3/2), 0], [0, -√(2/3), √(4/3)]]."},{"key":"C","text":"The Cholesky decomposition exists because A is symmetric positive definite."},{"key":"D","text":"A is an M-matrix because it is symmetric, positive definite, and has non-positive off-diagonal entries."}],"correctAnswer":"D","explanation":"An M-matrix is defined as a matrix with non-positive off-diagonal entries and all positive principal minors. While A has non-positive off-diagonal entries and is SPD, being an M-matrix is not equivalent to being positive definite; M-matrices are actually a subclass of positive semidefinite matrices, not all SPD matrices are M-matrices (some have positive eigenvalues but are not M-matrices).","difficulty":"hard"}]}